Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation in the eurozone is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 countries of the eurozone, inflation was higher than expected in November – after 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, according to the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
In contrast to the US, British and Canadian central bank, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered interest rates; in its discretion, the interest rate cut would favour rising commodity prices and the slight fall in unemployment, leading to the emergence of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB aims to keep the inflation rate below 2%, or at least close to the two-percent mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in a state of turmoil: inflation has to be “reconciled” in order to rule out the need for further action.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate in Germany reached a 12-year record high in November; in Spain the rate climbed from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Increased food and energy prices are responsible for rising inflation in the eurozone.
MATIF wheat prices rose 88 percent, and soybean prices also reached a record high since 1973.
Food oil and dairy products also experienced a significant deterioration in 2007.
The world market price of crude oil rose by 52 percent this year – last month, the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly US$100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 per cent in 2008 to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it is expected to fall to 1.9 per cent.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3% inflation rate, but the average annual rate is 2.1%.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
Gallup Determines Government Crisis
After long stagnation, the number of Fidesz sympathizers has grown significantly until the beginning of December, the party has the largest base camp for the first time since 2002, while the support for the socialists has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
The difference among party-like voters is clear thanks to the high determination of opposition supporters: more than two-thirds (71 percent) are opposed to a fifth (20 percent) of support for the MSZP.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary threshold: they reach two percent of the total population.
The number of party voters in both camps has grown by one percent.
Compared to the last low, the overall economic sentiment has deteriorated further - never before has the proportion of those who judge the country's economic situation as "extremely bad" been so high (41 percent), while another 46 percent consider it "quite bad".
After more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, the families see the change in their financial situation again more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects the situation to deteriorate further; only one-tenth is expected to improve.
A Gallup survey conducted in December found that 71% of respondents — a historic high — rated the prime minister’s work as “better bad than right.”
Thirteen percent of respondents generally have great confidence or confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány, while the share of supporters for Viktor Orbán accounts for 38 percent.
Some 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared with 27% distrust of the party leader of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of people who think that one could manage dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister even without a change of government.
After the riots last October, 35% had spoken out for the remainder of the government and the head of government, this share is now only 20%, while the relative majority (33%) sees the solution only in new elections.
Asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent replied that they would “safely” participate, and another 20 percent would “probably” cast their vote.
For comparison: if the parliamentary elections were to take place on Sunday, only 55 percent would go to the polls "with certainty", another 15 percent consider their participation "probable".
74% would vote against the tuition fees, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% against the hospital day allowance.
Turned to the group of participants in the referendum "with certainty" the proportions of opponents of the study, practice and hospital fees would be 81, 84, and 89 percent, respectively.
