Savings on disinfectants in many places
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds, the overload of the staff - all factors that are not exactly conducive to the containment of infections, according to the senior physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed in the traumatology department of János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was a similar infection.
The injured person in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but shortly thereafter the man had to return with an MRSA infection. A major operation could not be performed since because of the bacterium that is still in the patient’s body.
By December 10 of this year, 1094 hospitals reported infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to the senior physician of the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have certainly been recorded in hospitals, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of the infections (683 cases) were triggered by MRSA, the methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their nose without it causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as throat inflammation, tonsil inflammation, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the agents are dosed too high or used improperly, antibiotic-resistant bacteria develop, which spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently malfunctioning immune system, but also in older, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of János Hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of everyday hospital life.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA does not exist only where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
“Such patients are being isolated, the caregiver wears rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for treatment,” says Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are examined for MRSA when they are hospitalized, an infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rarely
The majority of MRSA-induced infections in hospitals would be preventable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavorable for the containment of the multidrug-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the admitted patients and isolate MRSA-infected immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not so often practiced in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no grants from the state health insurance for this investigation.
Most cases therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
On the part of the European Union, there are strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases in Hungary.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, that is, microbiological tests are necessary so that no resistance to the agent can develop, but this directive is also not always complied with by hospitals.
Among the outpatients, or patients in primary care, microbiological sampling is even rarer, says Karolina Böröcz.
Savings on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted by caregivers from one patient to another.
This is precisely why hand washing or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in this area in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but there is not always the possibility of isolating the infected patient in the local hospitals.
The rooms are even often overcrowded, the beds lined closely together, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz continues to point out, unfortunately, in the financially less well-off hospitals it even happens that disinfectants are saved, there are few caregivers, many patients - all factors that favor the development of infections.
Such infections are demonstrably far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government program against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes enormous costs to health insurance companies, so they are fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was included in the government program.
After the first signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has made prevention of multidrug-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
