A further EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three loan agreements worth EUR 400 million in Budapest on Friday, the money will go to education, transport and environmental protection infrastructure and the energy industry.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million framework for the financing of transport and environmental protection projects carried out with grants from the Cohesion Fund. The 100 million loan agreement was signed earlier and the current agreement deals with the use of the EUR 200 million awarded.
The sum of EUR 150 million agreed in the loan agreement will also be spent on the budgetary financing of educational projects.
The EIB has granted a total of EUR 300 million for this purpose to Hungary, and the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later in the context of the extension of the credit agreement.
In the area of innovation, the contracting parties have signed an agreement worth EUR 50 million, which will mainly be invested in research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
At the meeting, the subway line 4 was also discussed.
It was agreed that once Hungary has clarified the details of subway financing with the EU, the original contract and any modifications will be re-discussed.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects worth EUR 8.4 billion in Hungary.
The loan interest is EURIBOR-bound, the loan is provided by the EIB with a deferral of 8 years, free of commission.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - all of Europe is paying close attention to the previously rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who still buys the cheapest market in the EU, but which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is currently undoubtedly the most coveted pavement for real estate purchases in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Among the mountains are the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa among the most popular, by the sea are Albena, the "gold coast", the "sun coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the racers, but properties around Kavarna and Balcik are also in increasing demand.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior of the country will sooner or later attract investors, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the extremely favorable area of Russia registers more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers attractive offers - commercial and office spaces offer the highest returns.
Bulgaria is on its way to becoming one of the most attractive European golfing paradises, attracting tourists in addition to the summer and winter seasons as well as in the other two seasons.
Forward-looking investors are already buying on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy real estate in Bulgaria also want to change their lifestyle.
Most of the buyers are English, but there are also interested people from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while the Black Sea and ski resorts are predominantly Russian buyers.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle will either buy revitalized properties for 50-100,000 euros, or run-down houses for 5-15,000 euros, which they will then renovate themselves.
Good connections and accessibility as well as communication options are very important, but also the proximity to a large city, shops and doctors are crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed in the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group consists of business people who invest with the aim of increasing their value in the medium to long term.
Real estate in the capital, however, is becoming increasingly expensive due to the ever-increasing demand.
Within the EU, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but in the last five years there has been an annual increase of 21 percent.
The increase in real estate prices far exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the Six Hungarian Percentages
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will conclude on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries discuss the Bali roadmap, which sets the emission-reducing measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the expiry of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a fierce debate between developed and developing countries.
The United States has already signaled that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but it would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other big question at the conference is whether the industrialized countries are prepared to support developing countries financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement was also reached on the support of developing countries.
The Adaptation Fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, expected to be part of the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as reflected in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's 6%
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to achieve a new international agreement by 2009.
The minister declared that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (as measured by 1990 values), regardless of whether or not the "2012 agreement" will be successfully achieved. The Union would even be willing to push for a 30% reduction, provided that other major industrialised countries in the world, or developing countries, are also willing to fulfil their commitments to the fullest extent possible and responsibly.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the target of the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 per cent, whereas the EU and its 15 member states had already committed themselves to a minus of 8 per cent.
The target for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to the years 1985-87 - a target that the country will certainly meet, as can be seen in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The commitment is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not enter into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction project set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new international emission reduction system, the importance of which also the IPCC, the international, with the UN Nobel Peace Prize awarded, has highlighted in its recent scientific report the UN Climate Change Co.
This would delay the emission reduction, and increasing the Earth’s average temperature by more than 2°C would be unavoidable, resulting in extremely serious and irreparable consequences, according to scientists.
British Army advertises on YouTube
British Army units have posted footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan for the purpose of increasing popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Special forces stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations conducted against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reports.
The shots, shot with miniature cameras mounted on helmets, are checked at the air force base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are posted on the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such shots, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defense was registered under "defenseheadquarters" in spring 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Commonwealth Office) and the Iraqi-based international peacekeeping forces (MNFI) have their own YouTube channels.
Operations in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force released the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defense says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual objectives of the foreign missions.
Propaganda published in this way is almost free compared to conventional television advertisements, according to defense expert Gordon Mackenzie at the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message, as they confirm the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans advertise with game
However, the army must also fight against amateur footage, which, in addition to the carefully processed, censored footage, also makes it into the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: in the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the losses are talked about at most, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
Of the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan, by the way, numerous videos shot in use have already been uploaded to the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this "genus" for themselves.
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "Amerikas Army", in which the player can slip into the skin of the soldier as part of a more or less life-saving simulation.
