Holidays are not holidays everywhere
In Hungary, public holidays are strictly regulated by law, so that the practice of reorganizing the working days around the holidays has now become established, but the coming year gives us fewer such days.
In the EU and in America, something else is also referred to as a holiday.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and non-working days.
Unemployed days are usually ecclesiastical holidays, or are associated with significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: Both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are work-free days - the latter alone allows New Year's Eve celebrations to rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The public holidays are March 15, which commemorates the Revolution of 1848, and October 23, which commemorates the Revolution of 1956.
On the 20th of August, the foundation of the state, on the 1st of May the work is celebrated, on the 1st and 2nd of November we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of “workday shift” has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is ultimately to be worked out, has for many years been determined by the Minister of Labour in his own regulation.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and employees, public employees and civil servants.
Excluded are only companies and facilities where the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on holidays.
This year, the working regulations are only confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from December 24, life in this country remains formally standing, since most take time balance for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve, or the holiday specially cancelled for it.
Next year, more holidays fall into the middle of the week or into the end of the week, so there will be fewer re-arrangements on working days than this year.
The calendar is first "upside down" around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday, April 26, will be a working day so that Friday, May 2 can be a rest day.
The second re-arrangement is related to the holiday on October 23: On Saturday, October 18, you will have to work on Friday, October 24 in advance.
However, the end of the year will be completely in the sign of the holidays, after December 24, everything will be left and stopped, even if New Year’s Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six scary little things to annoy coworkers
Emails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never receive - harmless lies that we no longer notice at all: they bring "color" to everyday life in the workplace.
The question is whether to get used to these little inconveniences, or to better face the challenge and try to consciously avoid these misunderstandings for other annoying situations.
-Tips.
“Sorry, I forgot to direct you that someone from the marketing department called,” says one colleague.
That you missed a meeting?
At best, you regret it and try to make up for it again, perhaps by calling the marketing department and confessing regretfully that you forgot to align the message (this is the less common method).
Most of the time, the matter is dismissed with an apology.
Before you get caught up in embarrassing excuses, you should think about what you can do to give your colleagues really unpleasant moments and try to consciously avoid these situations.
Do you borrow something that doesn’t belong to you?
There’s hardly anything more annoying than picking up a document, office accessories, or the phone, but it’s not there.
Yesterday the stapler was still on the desk - this morning it is gone?
Or is the lost ballpoint pen discovered on a colleague’s desk?
Without asking, you should not borrow anything from colleagues, because they are rightly upset when they find that something has gone away.
So, don’t put envelopes or post-it from the office in your pocket, because it could hit you yourself: no more when you need it urgently.
Talking about the private life of your colleagues?
There is no effective way to stop a gossip that has already been put into the world.
Who did what with whom?
Where and why?
One should not tie the information (or assumptions) about the private life of colleagues to everyone’s nose if possible!
And if someone opens up and reveals his Inner Secret to us, we should not abuse that trust!
It is best to keep silent like a tomb instead of aligning those who are not present, even if others are aware of your colleague’s problems.
Reported sick for no reason?
If you call in the office to report sick, citing painful headaches, because you are feeling uncomfortable, or just want to rest, you should be aware of one thing: Your own work, unavoidable tasks, projects with fixed appointments must now be done by your colleagues instead of yourself.
So don’t play badly with your colleagues!
If you already know the day before that you won’t make it to the office the next day, or that something could happen in between, so you have to stay at home, you should report it in time so that neither the colleagues nor the boss are confronted unexpectedly with the absence.
Sum, Smile, Phone
One is just deepened in his work, but is suddenly disturbed by the loud yelling of the colleagues?
Are you listening to a phone call that you shouldn’t have heard?
One should not annoy one’s colleagues with humming, singing, loud conversations (which one has over their heads), cramping, constant insults or nagging.
All of this can be very disruptive, even if you aren’t deeply involved in a task (writing, planning, organizing).
Is it always the others’ fault?
If a project is not finished on time, you have forgotten to send an important letter or important messages, you should not look for the blame of your own forgetfulness with others!
If possible, you should not talk about the chaos in the office or the loud colleagues!
It is best to confess your mistakes and apologize if others have been affected!
The question of how to make up for the mistake or to make up for what has been missed is all too appropriate!
In the office - a feeling like at home?
Training pants and slips: Comfortable for at home, but has lost nothing in the office!
Even then you should not dress so casually if the workplace would actually allow it!
Just don't get too sloppy - you should respect both your colleagues and yourself so much that you dress appropriately in the office - if desired, also pretty and elegant!
