Banks want to deal with crisis
The U.S. Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of the United Kingdom, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together against the crisis in the financial markets.
More than $100 billion will go to the currency markets through auctions.
At these auctions, banks auction interest rates at which they are willing to lend each other money.
For example, the U.S. Fed is sending $40 billion to auction, another 24 making it loose for the European and Swiss central bank.
It is the first time since the attacks of September 11, that the central banks of the individual states have agreed on such a coordinated approach to deter or mitigate the consequences of a financial crisis.
“This step is intended to eliminate the biggest difficulties of the economy, i.e. the increasing lack of freely available capital that banks can lend,” Bernard Baumohl of the Economic Outlook Group wrote in a report for his clients.
“Coordinated action by central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the U.S. from 65% to about 50%,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unused loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect further billions of losses.
“Central banks must have been really afraid of what could be done when they decided to do so,” said Kieran Davies, chief economist at ABN Amro.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he said.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to bonds, loans will also become more expensive for their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the American economy into a recession, potentially impacting economic growth around the world.
The central banks have decided to do so after failing to lower the so-called LIBOR, the London interbank rate used for lending between banks.
This means that the banks were constantly afraid to lend to each other money, even though the central banks of the US, Canada and the UK had lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
“This will have the same effect as a further cut in interest rates,” Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts believe that this step by the central banks is helping to heat up the crisis because it does not solve the fundamental problem, namely the case of the U.S. real estate market.
