Cuba - the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday, that will come true if you just choose the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is calm like a pond.
Palms and All Inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and enchanting cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this to an abundant extent.
Only on one island, however, you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Greater Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana once became a camp or transit camp of treasures that the Spaniards had robbed in America and then transported to Europe.
Then came the American epoch.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the end of the 20th century.
It was built by one of the chiefs of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered a crime in the United States (especially during the Prohibition) was seen and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were among others.
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, skyscrapers grew, cars drove across the wide boulevards, which were among the cult symbols of the fifties of the last century.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Coj<0xC3><0xAD>mar he had his yacht.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, stars of the show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
What about today?
You can also leave your autograph on the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana.
Cocktails can be mixed at the bar at Hotel Nacional.
And the cult cars of the fifties are still driving around in Havana today, because the once imported Schigulis and Fiats have long since fallen apart in the salty and humid air.
Although Havana, in particular its oldest part, has fallen heavily, there is nowhere in the vicinity so many wonderful colonial sights as here.
Other places are being cleaned out, for example Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings much-needed money, there was a green light for this development.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have been created not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holgu<0xC3><0xAD>n and also on islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a marotte that is unique in the world and attracts railway lovers in particular.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam and diesel-driven narrow tracks to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and this is how you see cute and fully functioning locomotives, whose peers have long been in the museum elsewhere.
Excursions
The most important places do not miss the majority of visitors to Cuba.
It is no longer necessary to write about Varadero or Havana in detail.
It is worth mentioning that there is a museum in Hemingway’s property, which should not be missed by anyone who likes this writer.
The Vi<0xC3><0xB1>ales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on limestone soil.
The mogotas, lime cliffs and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, in their cavities fertile soil accumulated, through which also weathered rock areas are covered by dense growth.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet him when you visit one of Havana’s cigar factories.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was shot there.
Trinidad (disambiguation)
An ancient city that was founded shortly after the Spaniards had colonized the island.
The trade in slaves and sugar brought her fame and wealth.
The wealth was embodied in the beauty of the small town.
Spanish colonial architecture, heavily influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed in the last four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is so remote that there was no road there in the 1950s that would have connected the area with the rest of the country.
This isolation helped to leave it unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing torn down, everyone was glad that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than an afternoon time for Trinidad, it is worth seeing interesting places in the area, such as the beach Playa Ancón or the "Valley of Sugar Factories".
In the evening you should then go to the Casa de la M<0xC3><0xBA>sica, which revives after dark, and where the music does not remain silent until the morning.
Baracoa
This small town in the east of Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful of the island.
Certainly this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads that lead from Guantánamo to it have to overcome high and rugged mountains and pass through a landscape hardly touched by human intervention.
This eastern outpost of Cuba was included by UNESCO in its World Heritage list thanks to its untouched nature.
There the best chocolate is made, in the church you can see the cross of Columbus (in reality it was created about a hundred years after the trips of Columbus), and from the hill where the former castle stands, the present Hotel El Castillo, you can see several table mountains, of which El Yunque is the best known.
About the coffee, the rum, the cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountains, the bay of pigs and the island of Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patroness Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion to which the descendants of slaves profess, you could write many pages about all this.
But, as they say, it is better to look at it with your own eyes.
