For giving a name to a teddy bear, she was presented today to a court in Khartoum.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who had been accused in Sudan of insulting Islam, was sentenced on Thursday evening by a court in Khartoum to 15 days in prison and subsequent expulsion.
The British woman was accused of allowing six- to seven-year-old pupils to name a teddy bear Muhammad, although any depiction of the Islamic prophet is prohibited.
She deserved to be flogged.
After parents of pupils complained several times to the Sudanese Ministry of Culture, the 54-year-old elementary school teacher, who worked at Khartoum’s Unity High School, was taken home on Sunday and accused of insulting Islam under Article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code.
In fact, this matter begins in September when the teacher asks her six- to seven-year-old pupils to pick a name for the class teddy.
The children suggest eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed, reports school principal Robert Boules.
Finally, as the class votes, 20 out of 23 children choose Mohammed as their favorite first name.
Surely, Mohammed is the name of the Islamic prophet, but above all also a given name very common in Sudan.
Subsequently, the children created a book for the class, with the photo of the bear on it and the caption My name is Mohammed.
The bear himself did not carry a shield with that name, but the problem is quite simple that the depiction of the Islamic prophet is considered an insult to Islam.
One of the Muslim colleagues of Gillian Gibbons, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, explained that he knew her well, and she would never have done anything that would have brought her close to a religious faith, I only regret that she asked the children to vote for a name, in his opinion this is only an innocent mistake.
An opinion shared by numerous students of the teacher, who describe it as being very attentive to their students and as a person who never talks about religion in class.
Keep in mind that the first name Mohammed is also the second most common name in the UK, for which there are 14 different spellings in English.
This given name, often chosen by Muslim families, is considered a kind of devotion to the prophet (it is often given to the firstborn of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this first name?
For example, can you give it to a toy?
This is, of course, a matter of interpretation.
