Spectacular repair at the space station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his comrades from the International Space Station (ISS) crew will have spent more than seven hours in space to perform the spectacular repair of a defective solar collector, which is essential for the continuation of scientific work on the station.
A daring exit, which has achieved several records due to its duration, the removal of habitable modules, the speed with which it was organized, and the tools crafted by the astronauts to perform the repair.
The problem occurred on Wednesday when astronauts unloaded the Harmony module from the spacecraft Discovery, a large cylindrical part that will soon house the European and Japanese scientific laboratories.
This module is a kind of landing bridge for the module laboratories.
But you have to be able to supply them with electricity.
The crew’s second task was to implement a 17.5-tonne solar panel power generation module that was already on the ISS to bring it to its final position.
After moving it, the crew began to restructure the solar panels of the module, whose span is 76 meters.
And it happened that one of the collectors that can be folded up like accordions was damaged by a jammed cable over a length of about one meter.
The restructuring was stopped so as not to further damage the collector.
The astronauts, who were originally supposed to leave the space shuttle Discovery and then repair another solar collector whose rotation system was faulty, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was chosen to walk around at the end of the 30-metre long remote-controlled arm of the space shuttle that had been attached to the station to carry out the repair.
He is one of NASA’s best spacewalkers.
Large, resilient, very skillful, it has a well-developed upper body and long arms.
The 46-year-old trained doctor was chosen to operate on the injured solar panel.
After carefully inspecting the damage, he cut through the faulty cable and attached a kind of rail to the damaged spot.
He was supported by a second spacewalker, who remained near the lock, and, from inside, by the other astronauts, among them Peggy Whitson, commander of the crew.
The tool he used, a mini hockey stick, wrapped with insulator to prevent an electric shock on the solar panels that generate several hundred volts, the astronauts aboard the station had devised and crafted.
When the action was over, Scott Parazynski waited until the collector was fully unfolded before counting his tools and returning to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed half a day of relaxation, before today seven astronauts returned to the space shuttle Discovery to presumably make the return flight to Earth Wednesday.
