A new festival is born
Following numerous rumors about the creation of a new music festival in Philadelphia by C3 Presents, the promoter/producer announces the Vineland Music Festival in New Jersey, in collaboration with Festival Republic of British producer Melvin Benn.
“It’s an honor for our company to work with a person who has served, no more and no less, as a role model for the current festival movement in America,” Charlie Jones of C3 told Bilboard.com.
C3 hosts the Lollapalooza Festival in Chicago and the Austin City Limits Music Festival.
Vineland, New Jersey, is a summer camping destination.
The festival will probably take place from August 8th to 10th on a 500 acre private farm about 40 minutes from Philadelphia.
The director of Festival Republic Melvin Benn, formerly known as Mean Fiddler, is one of the producers of the most prestigious festivals in the world.
In 1989, he took over the management of the Reading Festival in the United Kingdom, which attracts around 80,000 people annually.
In 1999, Melvin Benn added the Leeds Festival to his portfolio, and then, in 2006, Festival Republic created the Latitude Festival at Henham Park in Suffolk.
Since 2002, Melvin Benn has been co-owner of the Glastonbury Festival, which can now accommodate up to 177,500 people.
Charlie Jones of C3, who describes Glastonbury as the most inspiring event he’s ever been to, says his company and that of Melvin Benn are working alongside each other to provide the area with a European-style festival event.
“We have selected Philadelphia as a market and are eager to work with the Fairmount Park Commission to create a festival in downtown Philadelphia,” says Charlie Jones.
We were negotiating with the city and the Commission was motivated and enthusiastic about this project.
“Unfortunately, we have been stuck in political debates about the current administration,” continues Charlie Jones.
Fortunately, we were able to discuss with Melvin Benn and we are making preparations to create a great festival in an extraordinary place that will ultimately benefit the population.”
C3 Presents brought the 2005 Lollapalooza Festival back to life at Grand Park Chicago after profiling itself in the festival world in 2002 along with the Austin City Limits Music Festival.
The two events generated $9.8 million and $11.8 million in gross tax revenues in 2007 respectively.
These two festivals take place in an urban environment.
“Melvin Benn’s European model is a rural festival, whereas ours is more of an urban green space,” says Charlie Jones.
“The goal is to somehow merge these two concepts together to simultaneously convey the impression of a rural festival in the European and an urban one in the American way.”
Vineland is located about halfway between Philadelphia and Atlantic City.
“The community of Vineland, including the mayor, is taking the burden of this event with joy,” says Charlie Jones.
The latter refuses to disclose the terms of the agreement, but he confirms "that they are interesting enough to invest in such an event and to host a festival that will hopefully have a long life."
Charlie Jones says the festival's recording capacity is "very large", corresponding to about 80,000 people at the Bonnaroo Music Festival in Tennessee.
He says that the invitations were sent to the groups, but that nothing could be confirmed when they were printed.
“Vineland will offer tasteful rock, but the music will be very diverse, hoping to attract all kinds of viewers,” says Charlie Jones.
His partners with C3, which won the Top Independent Promoter Award at the last Bollboard Touring Awards, are Charlie Walker and Charles Attal.
