New fears over natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute looms between Ukraine and Russia, raising the risk of Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe being impaired.
The bulk of Russian natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) is conducted through Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge higher transit fees from Russia.
An earlier conflict between the two states last year reduced supplies to the EU states.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow is taking place at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine must pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine has to be charged more, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% additionally for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine has to pay 40% more for imports of Gazprom.
“It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks,” Ukraine’s economic minister Anatoli Kinakh told Reuters.
“The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] over Ukraine.”
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This resulted in a fall in exports to Western Europe, which drove prices up dramatically.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union’s supply.
Russia has the world’s largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom is supplementing its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS 'must control foreign workers'
The Scottish State Health Service must improve the checks of the criminal records for workers from outside Europe, said a member of the control body.
The recommendation of the chief financial controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was brought together in connection with the attack on Glasgow airport in June.
Black also expressed concerns that the Scottish state health service has no precise ideas about the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important checks were carried out correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The Chief Financial Controller investigated personnel recruited outside the European Economic Area following the attack on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after an off-road vehicle drove through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared on video at the Old Bailey in October and was charged in connection with the alleged car bomb attack in the UK.
It is expected that the State Health Service will carry out checks prior to the hiring of foreign employees to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorizations to work in the UK.
Although health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review criminal records, the agency does not have the authority to obtain this information outside of the UK.
The report of the chief auditor now states, among other recommendations, that the board should take up guidelines of the criminal record excerpt, which helps employers with checks in different countries.
"Although we found evidence of these checks in some personnel records, they were not routinely carried out," the report noted.
Black said the Scottish health authorities would follow their investigative guidelines heavily prior to hiring, but added: “Our report highlights areas where the system can be improved to ensure accurate information about the number of foreign health service employees is available.”
BMA Scotland chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was “extremely unlikely” that investigations would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks in advance of hiring potential NHS employees.
“The report says that the NHS Scotland’s current pre-employment tests are working well and it’s not clear what added value the recommendations will provide,” he said.
Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number is likely to be higher, also because the boards have problems identifying those employees who are on leave indefinitely.
The investigation further found that established control procedures by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian have been predominantly followed.
These include passport, work permit, and qualification controls.
The Scottish government is currently reviewing its policies and guidelines for pre-employment checks for foreign staff in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: “I was concerned to do this work in the face of the terror attack at Glasgow Airport.”
She added that the Scottish government, in conjunction with health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that best practices would be reflected in updated guidelines on pre-employment screenings by all employees, including those from abroad, scheduled to be released next month.
