Venus is the hellish twin of Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere on Earth, Venus is more similar than previously thought: The European spacecraft "Venus Express" has detected lightning in the atmosphere and wind swirls at the poles, as they occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that it is flashing on Venus.
Now, the European probe Venus Express has provided the proof - it sensed electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: The lightning on Venus shoots at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine Nature.
According to the famous "original soup theory", lightning has created life on Earth: thunderstorms are said to have stimulated reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: “If there ever was life there, it must have been in very early history,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees Celsius.
"Venus may be Earth's devil's twin, but it's a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar in mass and size to Earth, has undergone such an entirely different evolution is the basic question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as since the early 1990s no spacecraft has been dedicated to the exploration of this planet.
The latest research findings, which are now presented in several “Nature” articles, not only underscore the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system, the researchers believe.
"They also show that our neighboring planet's similarities with Earth are greater than initially thought," the ESA said.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud swirl at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the winter hemisphere, writes a research team led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is nearly as large with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, orbits the sun in just under 225 days.
But it turns much slower around itself: a day of Venus lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus’ surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar are hardly reminiscent of Earth, scientists assume that both planets were created under very similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated, which remained on Earth in oceans, but on which Venus was lost to space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed on Earth in carbonate rocks, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
