These aren't Warhol's boxes.
Whoever connects the terms Sweden and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently in Sweden made wooden boxes cast dark shadows on Warhol's work directory.
The majority of the ninety-four Brillo boxes of the "type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes of the year 1968, internal investigations at the Moderna Museum in Stockholm now come to a sobering result: The six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén has given to the Moderna Museum in Stockholm in 1995, are also well-deserved by the copy of the "One"
Prehistory is intertwined, a confusing intertwining of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard boxes of the "Brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 exhibited - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of cardboard Brillo boxes: these did not come (for cost reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo Cardboard Factory.
They were not works of art, but their models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably gave permission in 1968 to have a few Brillo wooden crates produced in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses now speak of around fifteen boxes, which at that time were rightly entered into art and auction history as authorized original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the designation "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have made more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later erroneously claimed that around one hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, it was not until 1990 that Hultén’s 105 boxes were produced in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator at the Moderna Museet, has investigated, in addition to the six museum-owned Brillo boxes, three of which were privately owned by Sweden, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press chipboards were first primed and thawed, after which white oil paint was applied with a brush.
On the other hand, the structure of the 1990 copies reveals that the paint was applied directly to the press panel with a paint roller without primer - in addition, it is not oil paint, but acrylic paint.
“These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol’s Brillo boxes,” says Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet: “Unless the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York comes to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will release the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibitions.”
In July, however, the Authentication Board announced that it would pursue the “serious accusations” raised in the matter of soap powder boxes.
But since then they have been shrouded in relentless silence.
